title: Rules for the Design of Water Supply Systems, Ventura County, Calif.
items.abstract: <jats:p>This article discusses the expansion of water service by many existing water purveyors in Ventura County, California. Before 1957, there was no regulation by the county of water supply systems except in the case of residential subdivisions, and this regulation consisted of only two parts. These requirements could be met without even having a system which could serve water, as nothing required the well to be connected to the water mains. It was discovered that county control of water supply systems being installed by land developers is necessary to insure an adequate supply of water for both domestic service and fire protection. An appendix to the article contains the Water Supply Requirements for Subdivisions, Planned Developments, and Trailer Parks; Technical Provisions of Resolution No. 3333, Ventura County Planning Commission, Aug. 14, 1961.</jats:p>

title: THE EFFECT OF MALNUTRITION AND OF OCCLUDING THE HEPATIC BLOOD SUPPLY ON THE REMOVAL OF TRITIATED CORTICOSTEROIDS
items.abstract:
<jats:title>SUMMARY</jats:title>
        <jats:p>Acute occlusion of the blood supply to the liver decreases inactivation of tritiated cortisol, corticosterone and aldosterone. In malnourished animals which had lost approx. 25% of their initial body weight, only cortisol inactivation was decreased.</jats:p>
